  "nursesNote": "Restraints and seclusion are a last resort, used only to prevent a patient from harming self or others after less restrictive measures (de-escalation, redirection) have failed. They require a provider order and are time-limited (about 4 hours for adults, shorter for children) and may never be used for punishment, staff convenience, or as a standing PRN order. The nurse uses the least restrictive effective type, monitors the patient frequently or continuously, and provides circulation, skin, toileting, hydration, and range-of-motion care. Quick-release knots are tied to the bed frame, and restraints are removed as soon as the patient meets release criteria.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Use restraints only as a last resort for safety",
    "Obtain a time-limited provider order",
    "Apply the least restrictive effective type",
    "Monitor frequently and provide skin, circulation, and toileting care",
    "Reassess and release as soon as criteria are met"
  ],
